  "market_regime": {
    "title": "Market Regime",
    "composite": "Composite",
    "description": "Six independent pillars score together to locate the market within its cycle. It answers how much risk you should carry — not what to buy — guiding your position posture so you don't react late at regime transitions.",
    "score_suffix": "/12",
    "guidance_label": "Configuration",
    "earnings": "Earnings",
    "valuation": "Valuation",
    "fed": "Fed policy",
    "economic": "Economic data",
    "credit": "Credit",
    "sentiment": "Sentiment",
    "earnings_desc": "Are companies still making money, more than last year? Strong growth (>10%) with analysts upgrading = 10; modest growth = 5; profits shrinking = 0. Earnings are the foundation — bull markets without them don't last.",
    "valuation_desc": "Are stocks expensive right now? Compares price to next-year earnings (PE) and 10-year average earnings (CAPE). Cheap = 10; fair = 5; pricey = 0. The richer valuations get, the less room for upside and the more fragile to bad news.",
    "fed_desc": "Is the Fed adding liquidity or pulling it back? Cutting rates = 10; on hold or hinting at cuts = 5; hiking or turning hawkish = 0. Low rates lift risk assets; high rates weigh on them — the single most powerful macro lever.",
    "economic_desc": "Is the economy itself healthy? Unemployment, payrolls, the inflation cluster (Core PCE, CPI, PPI, 3-month direction), plus industrial production as the manufacturing read. Stable jobs + cooling inflation + IP expanding = 10; weak jobs, reaccelerating inflation, or IP contracting = 0. PPI leads CPI, and IP turning negative is a classic recession tell.",
    "credit_desc": "Will the bond market lend to companies? Watches the spread between junk bonds and Treasuries. Tight spreads (cheap borrowing) = 10; middle = 5; widening (markets nervous) = 0. Credit usually smells trouble before stocks do — early warning.",
    "sentiment_desc": "How extreme is market sentiment? Read backwards. Low VIX + balanced retail = 10; neutral = 5; VIX spike or extreme retail bullishness = 0. When everyone's bullish you're often near a top; extreme fear is usually opportunity.",
    "sparkline_unavailable": "No history yet",
    "six_dimensions": "Six dimensions",
    "scores_refresh_twice_weekly": "Scores refresh twice weekly",
    "updated_daily_dimensions": "Updated {date}",
    "updated_label": "as of {date}",
    "regime_label": {
      "expansion": "Expansion",
      "neutral_expansion": "Neutral expansion",
      "watch": "Watch",
      "stress": "Stress",
      "bear": "Bear"
    },
    "guidance_text": {
      "maintain_equity": "Pillars are aligned — earnings breadth and credit jointly support risk assets, and the Fed stance is not yet restrictive. Hold both quality growth and cyclicals; treat pullbacks as adds, not as regime signals. Watch for breadth narrowing and widening credit spreads as the first cracks.",
      "hold_no_leverage": "Composite is still constructive but pillars have begun to diverge — expansion momentum is no longer uniform. Maintain exposure without stretching: no new leverage, no high-beta tails. A single-pillar slip in credit or earnings is the trigger to de-risk, not a buy-the-dip prompt.",
      "reduce_beta": "Multiple pillars are softening together — the expansion narrative is eroding but not yet broken. Rotate out of high-beta and crowded growth into quality cash flows, low-vol defensives, and duration; wait for credit to stabilize and at least one pillar to re-strengthen before bottom-fishing.",
      "heavy_reduce": "Regime has turned defensive — credit stress, earnings cuts, or macro weakness now dominate. Cut equity meaningfully, raise cash, add gold and duration to hedge tail risk. Rallies here are typically counter-trend; capital preservation outweighs relative-return risk.",
      "defensive": "Bear regime confirmed with broad-based deterioration. Hold defensive posture, sell into strength rather than chase rallies. Track three bottom signals — credit spreads peaking, earnings revisions troughing, Fed pivot — and don't front-run recovery until at least two align."
    }
  },
